ce:section.ce:para:
To further realize the rapid identification of GB in Ningxia, Xinjiang, Gansu, Inner Mongolia and Qinghai, we integrated spectral data from different origins using chemometrics and established a PLS-DA model. The classification results are presented in 
                           Table 1. The PLS-DA model identified 85.4% by raw fluorescence spectrum. However, after adding CdTe-QDs @ N-CDs, the recognition accuracy of fluorescence spectra increased to 97.9%. The analysis results of the original fluorescence spectrum data by PLS-DA (Fig. S9
                           ) showed that the GB samples in Ningxia, Gansu and Qinghai were misjudged. In contrast, the recognition rate of PLS-DA on nano-effects fluorescence was improved, and the misinterpretation rate was significantly reduced.

As shown in Fig. S8, GB extracts from different origins showed weak blue, and the difference in visual fluorescence between different origins was relatively insignificant. Therefore, it was difficult to distinguish directly by original color of GB alone. However, after adding the single-channel visual sensor CdTe-QDs @ N-CDs, causing a series of visible fluorescent differences, ranging from orange to pink, purple, and blue due to different component proportions and their interactions (
                           Fig. 6
                           ).

The raw visual RGB values of the PLS-DA model were identified by 68.9% (
                           Table 1
                           ). However, with adding CdTe-QDs@N-CDs, the recognition accuracy of visual RGB values increased to 93.3%. The results showed that the PLS-DA identification results of GB were significantly improved by using the CdTe-QDs @ N-CDs nanomaterials, which can realize the rapid visual identification of GB from five large producing areas. This indicated that the CdTe-QDs @ N-CDs had high sensitivity, specificity and accuracy in identifying GB origin with good classification performance.
